@flexiarg forward-model/the-forward-model-is-a-pattern-cascade
@title Model The Future Build As A Pattern Cascade, Not A Mission List
@sigils [⟡/?]
@audience futon stack operators, agents, forward-model authors
@tone conjectural
@style pattern

! conclusion: Characterize the future build as a typed cascade of design patterns, boxes are patterns, wires are slot-adjacency, holes are patterns that should exist and do not, rather than as a list of missions.

  + context: Forward-model hypothesis, not yet attested. The meta-pattern of this namespace: the join of the attested War Room semilattice with the mission-level backlog cascade.

  + IF:
    The stack has both a retrospective strategy layer, attested rulings composed into a semilattice, and mission-level forward models such as the backlog cascade, and the design patterns are indexed and slot-queryable.

  + HOWEVER:
    Every existing forward model boxes the future as missions; none characterizes the future build through patterns, so the reusable form of how we build stays implicit in prose.

  + THEN:
    Model the next half-million lines as a cascade whose boxes are patterns and whose holes are the patterns that would have to be authored to reach the terminals, composed live from the indexed corpus rather than hand-drawn. The attested war-room patterns are the bottom; the forward-model hypotheticals are the frontier.

  + BECAUSE:
    Patterns are reusable where missions are one-off. A future modeled as patterns tells you not just what to build but the shape of building it, and it composes with the retrospective semilattice into one continuous actual-to-projected object, the thing no current artifact provides.

    + evidence: Bridge target, not yet attested. Would fuse the backlog-cascade merged forward model, mission-level, and the pipeline-pattern-cascade, hand-drawn, into a pattern-level forward model, realized by this forward-model namespace itself.
